        </div>
        <p class="mb-2">Some content also lives in curated local data files and generated stub files. This makes Canva, SlideShare, Finna, and Research.fi driven sections more stable when live fetching is unavailable or incomplete.</p>
        <p class="mb-2">Technically, these sources become tables, ticker highlights, cards, searchable views, metric counters, and automatically updated change lists. External embeds are routed through a consent layer before loading.</p>
        <p class="mb-0">The structure and some summarisation on analysis pages have been AI-assisted, but the final published content is still manually reviewed and accepted through version control.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card border-0 shadow-sm">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h2 class="h4 mb-3">4. Popular-level roadmap to build your own site</h2>
        <ol class="mb-0">
          <li>Bring AI in from step one: ask for a plan first, then implement in small, reviewable change batches.</li>
          <li>Create a GitHub repository and pick a simple stack (Eleventy + Bootstrap works well).</li>
          <li>Start small: one base template and a few pages.</li>
          <li>Add multilingual support only after your core structure works.</li>
          <li>Integrate one API at a time and give each source a cache or fallback path.</li>
          <li>Add quality checks early: build checks, SEO validation, and basic accessibility tests.</li>
          <li>Automate build and deploy with CI/CD and add at least a few production smoke tests.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>
